%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Variables}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Table~\ref{tab:variables} summarizes the observable variables employed throughout the empirical analyses, the role each plays in revealing the latent theoretical constructs, and the proposition to which each contributes. Rather than redefining the concepts introduced in the theoretical framework, the table clarifies how ministerial spell data are transformed into the indexed comparisons required by the empirical analyses.


\begin{table}[!htbp]
\centering
\caption{Operationalization of the Empirical Analysis}
\label{tab:variables}
\small
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.25}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{p{3.2cm}Xp{2.2cm}}
\toprule
\textbf{Observable variable} &
\textbf{Operation to reveal latent constructs} &
\textbf{Used to evaluate} \\
\midrule

Political Framework ($PF_f$) &
Indexes the historical environments within which ministerial duration is evaluated. Comparing $D_f$ across successive Political Frameworks reveals whether observed organizational continuity exhibits progressively longer patterns. Under Axioms~\ref{ax:continuity_knowledge} and~\ref{ax:knowledge_learning}, such patterns are interpreted as evidence regarding increasingly favorable conditions for organizational knowledge accumulation ($K$) and institutional learning ($IL$). &
P1 \\

\addlinespace

Portfolio ($p$) &
Indexes governmental organizations operating within each Political Framework. Comparing $D_{fp}$ across portfolios within the same Political Framework reveals whether organizational continuity differs systematically across governmental organizations. Under Axiom~\ref{ax:protective_belt}, these differences are interpreted as evidence consistent with differential Protective Belts ($PB$). &
P2 \\

\addlinespace

Presidential administration ($a$) &
Indexes executive contexts within which ministerial appointments and replacements occur. Conditioning on $D_{fpa}$ accounts for executive-level heterogeneity affecting ministerial duration independently of the theoretical mechanisms. &
Control \\

\addlinespace

Ministerial duration ($D$) &
Observed time in office. Depending on the analytical comparison, duration is summarized as $D_f$, $D_{fp}$, or $D_{fpa}$, providing the observable outcome through which the latent theoretical constructs are evaluated. &
P1, P2 \\

\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}

\vspace{0.2cm}

\begin{minipage}{0.97\textwidth}
\footnotesize
\textit{Note:} Organizational continuity ($C$), organizational knowledge accumulation ($K$), institutional learning ($IL$), and Protective Belts ($PB$) are latent theoretical constructs and are therefore not directly observed. Ministerial duration provides the observable indicator through which these constructs are evaluated under the deductive framework developed in Section~3.
\end{minipage}

\end{table}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Empirical Strategy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The empirical strategy follows directly from the deductive structure developed in Section~\ref{sec:theoretical_framework}. Each proposition generates a distinct observable implication and therefore requires a distinct empirical comparison. Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration} concerns historical variation across Political Frameworks, whereas Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration} concerns organizational variation across governmental portfolios operating within the same Political Framework. Although both propositions are evaluated using ministerial duration, they differ in the dimension along which duration is compared.

\paragraph{Historical comparison (P1).}

Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration} is evaluated by comparing ministerial duration across successive Political Frameworks. The analysis therefore indexes duration by Political Framework ($D_f$) and examines whether later Political Frameworks exhibit progressively longer patterns of ministerial duration than their predecessors. Kaplan--Meier estimates provide the initial visual assessment of this historical ordering, whereas pairwise Cox comparisons evaluate whether the observed differences are consistent with the progression implied by the proposition.

\paragraph{Organizational comparison (P2).}

Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration} is evaluated by comparing ministerial duration across governmental organizations operating within the same Political Framework. The analysis therefore indexes duration jointly by Political Framework and portfolio ($D_{fp}$), allowing organizational comparisons while holding the broader historical environment constant. Kaplan--Meier estimates describe the observed organizational differences, whereas pairwise Cox comparisons quantify the relative hazards associated with each organizational contrast.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Survival Analysis}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Survival analysis provides the statistical framework for evaluating both propositions because ministerial duration constitutes time-to-event data characterized by unequal observation periods and a small number of right-censored observations.

The empirical analyses proceed in two complementary stages. First, Kaplan--Meier estimators provide non-parametric descriptions of ministerial survival, allowing the observable implications of each proposition to be assessed directly from the empirical survival trajectories. Second, pairwise Cox proportional hazards models quantify the magnitude of the differences between the survival experiences of the relevant historical and organizational categories. Unlike a single reference-category specification, the pairwise comparisons evaluate every combination of Political Frameworks or governmental organizations, permitting the empirical analyses to identify where the historical or organizational trajectories depart from the theoretical expectations.

Model assumptions are evaluated using Schoenfeld residuals together with complementary graphical diagnostics.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Results}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Proposition 1: Ministerial Duration across Political Frameworks}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration} predicts that successive Political Frameworks should exhibit progressively longer patterns of ministerial duration. Its observable implication is therefore that ministers serving under later Political Frameworks should exhibit higher survival probabilities over time than ministers serving under earlier Political Frameworks. Under Axioms~\ref{ax:continuity_knowledge} and~\ref{ax:knowledge_learning}, progressively longer ministerial duration is interpreted as evidence of increasingly favorable organizational conditions for organizational knowledge accumulation and institutional learning.

Figure~\ref{fig:km_frameworks} presents the Kaplan--Meier survival estimates for the six Political Frameworks.

\subsubsection{Kaplan--Meier Estimates}
\begin{figure}
\centering
<<fig:km_epochs,echo=FALSE,fig=TRUE>>=
library(survival)
library(survminer)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF"))

km_epoch <- survfit(
  Surv(duration, event) ~ political_framework,
  data = datos_pcm_mef
)

s <- surv_summary(km_epoch) |>
  mutate(
    epoch = gsub("^political_framework=", "", strata)
  )

meds <- s |>
  group_by(epoch) |>
  slice_min(order_by = abs(surv - 0.5), n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) |>
  ungroup()

ann_df <- meds |>
  mutate(
    num = as.numeric(gsub("^([0-9]+).*", "\\1", political_framework)),
    ord = match(num, c(1, 2, 6, 5, 3, 4))
  ) |>
  arrange(ord) |>
  mutate(
    x_text = c(230, 360, 500, 640, 780, 920),
    y_text = c(.545, .550, .555, .560, .565, .570),
    label = as.character(num)
  )

ggplot(
  s,
  aes(
    x = time,
    y = surv,
    colour = as.ordered(political_framework),
    linetype = political_framework
  )
) +
  geom_step(linewidth = 1.5) +
  geom_hline(
    yintercept = 0.5,
    linetype = "dashed",
    colour = "grey50",
    alpha = 0.6
  ) +
  geom_point(
    data = ann_df,
    aes(x = time, y = 0.5),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    colour = "grey30",
    size = 0
  ) +
  geom_segment(
    data = ann_df,
    aes(x = x_text, y = y_text, xend = time, yend = 0.5),
    inherit.aes = FALSE,
    colour = "grey40",
    linewidth = 0.35
  ) +
  geom_label(
  data = ann_df,
  aes(x = x_text, y = y_text, label = label),
  inherit.aes = FALSE,
  hjust = 0.5,
  vjust = 0.5,
  size = 3.5,
  colour = "grey20",
  fill = "white",
  label.size = 0.25,
  fontface = "bold"
)+
  labs(
    x = "Ministerial duration in days",
    y = "Survival probability",
    colour = NULL,
    linetype = NULL
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(type = "div", palette = "Spectral") +
  theme_classic2() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(.75, .75),
    legend.background = element_rect(
      fill = "white",
      colour = "grey60"
    ),
    legend.key = element_blank()
  ) + annotate(
  "text",
  x = 1750,
  y = .51,
  label = "Median survival (S = 0.5)",
  hjust = 1,
  size = 3,
  colour = "grey20"
)
@
\caption{Kaplan–Meier estimates of ministerial continuity across political frameworks. Curves represent the estimated probability that a minister remains in office beyond a given duration. Numbers identify the six political frameworks listed in Table~\ref{tab:frameworks}. Analyses are restricted to appointments to the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM) and the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF).}
\label{fig:km_epochs}
\end{figure}


The Kaplan--Meier estimates provide an initial visual assessment of Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}. The proposition is intentionally formulated as a strong inequality. Rather than asking whether ministerial duration generally tends to increase over time, it requires each successive Political Framework to exhibit longer duration than its predecessor. This demanding formulation transforms the proposition into a diagnostic device, allowing the empirical analysis not only to assess the overall historical trajectory but also to identify the specific Political Frameworks at which that trajectory departs from monotonicity.

If successive Political Frameworks generated progressively more favorable organizational conditions for continuity, the median survival times should follow the historical ordering of the Political Frameworks. The numbered labels identify each Political Framework at the point where its estimated survival function reaches the median survival probability ($S=0.5$). Under complete support for Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}, the expected ordering would therefore be

\[
PF_1 < PF_2 < PF_3 < PF_4 < PF_5 < PF_6,
\]

where each successive Political Framework exhibits longer ministerial duration than its predecessor.

The observed ordering is only partially consistent with this expectation. Among the first four completed Political Frameworks, the median survival times increase monotonically, producing the ordering

\[
PF_1 < PF_2 < PF_3 < PF_4.
\]

This pattern is fully consistent with the proposition. The historical trajectory changes, however, with the fifth Political Framework, whose median ministerial duration falls below those observed under both the third and fourth Political Frameworks. The sixth Political Framework exhibits an even shorter median duration, although this result should be interpreted cautiously because it corresponds to an ongoing Critical Juncture rather than a completed Political Framework.

The strict formulation of Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration} is intentionally demanding. A weaker interpretation would require only that later Political Frameworks tend to exhibit longer ministerial duration than earlier ones, allowing occasional departures from strict monotonicity. Even under this more permissive interpretation, however, the fifth Political Framework remains historically distinctive because it reverses the trajectory established by the preceding completed Political Frameworks.

This departure from monotonicity should not be interpreted as contradicting the comparative-historical reconstruction developed by \textcite{lopez_jimenez_peru_2025}. That reconstruction identifies successive Political Frameworks as the enduring political legacies of completed Critical Junctures and argues that these legacies progressively broaden political incorporation and democratization. It does not propose that organizational continuity or institutional learning should improve monotonically over time. Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration} introduces a different theoretical question: whether these successive political legacies also generated progressively more favorable organizational conditions for institutional learning.

From this perspective, Figure~\ref{fig:km_epochs} suggests that political development and organizational learning need not follow identical historical trajectories. Organizational continuity appears to improve systematically across the first four completed Political Frameworks, but the post-1993 political settlement does not extend that earlier trajectory. Rather than representing a contradiction of the Critical Junctures framework, the fifth Political Framework identifies the point at which Peru's political evolution and the organizational conditions for institutional learning appear to diverge. The pairwise Cox analyses reported below quantify these historical differences and identify the Political Frameworks between which they become statistically distinguishable.



%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsubsection{Cox Proportional Hazards Model}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


The Kaplan--Meier estimates describe the observed historical trajectory of ministerial survival, but they do not estimate the magnitude of differences between Political Frameworks. To identify where the historical trajectory departs from the monotonic expectation implied by Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}, Table~\ref{tab:cox_pairwise_pf_matrix} reports pairwise Cox proportional hazards comparisons across Political Frameworks. Each cell compares the replacement hazard of the column Political Framework against the row Political Framework. Because the matrix involves multiple pairwise comparisons, reported $p$-values are adjusted using the Holm procedure for multiple comparisons.



<<tab:cox_pairwise_pf_matrix, results=tex, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
library(survival)
library(dplyr)
library(broom)
library(purrr)
library(tidyr)
library(stringr)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF")) |>
  mutate(
    political_framework = factor(as.character(political_framework))
  )

pf_levels <- levels(datos_pcm_mef$political_framework)

pairwise_cox <- combn(pf_levels, 2, simplify = FALSE) |>
  map_dfr(function(pair) {
    
    df_pair <- datos_pcm_mef |>
      filter(political_framework %in% pair) |>
      mutate(
        political_framework = relevel(
          factor(political_framework),
          ref = pair[1]
        )
      )
    
    fit <- coxph(
      Surv(duration, event) ~ political_framework,
      data = df_pair
    )
    
    out <- tidy(
      fit,
      exponentiate = TRUE,
      conf.int = TRUE
    )
    
    tibble(
      Reference = pair[1],
      Comparison = pair[2],
      HR = out$estimate,
      CI_low = out$conf.low,
      CI_high = out$conf.high,
      p_value = out$p.value
    )
  }) |>
  mutate(
    p_adj_holm = p.adjust(p_value, method = "holm"),
    HR_label = sprintf("%.2f", HR),
    CI_label = sprintf("[%.2f, %.2f]", CI_low, CI_high),
    p_label = format.pval(p_adj_holm, digits = 3, eps = .001),
    cell = paste0(HR_label, " (", p_label, ")")
  )

pairwise_matrix <- pairwise_cox |>
  select(Reference, Comparison, cell) |>
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = Comparison,
    values_from = cell
  ) |>
  arrange(match(Reference, pf_levels))

pairwise_matrix |>
  kbl(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    align = c("l", rep("c", length(pf_levels) - 1)),
    caption = "Pairwise Cox Comparisons across Political Frameworks",
    label = "cox_pairwise_pf_matrix",
    escape = FALSE
  ) |>
  kable_styling(
    latex_options = c("hold_position", "scale_down"),
    font_size = 8
  ) |>
  footnote(
    general = paste(
      "Cells report hazard ratios from pairwise Cox proportional hazards models, with Holm-adjusted p-values in parentheses.",
      "Each row category is the reference group; each column category is the comparison group.",
      "Hazard ratios below one indicate lower ministerial replacement hazard in the column Political Framework relative to the row Political Framework.",
      "Analyses are restricted to PCM and MEF appointments."
    ),
    threeparttable = TRUE,
    escape = FALSE
  )

@



The pairwise Cox comparisons confirm that the principal historical discontinuity separates the first two Political Frameworks from the subsequent completed Political Frameworks. Relative to PF1 and PF2, the hazards of ministerial replacement decline substantially under PF3, PF4, and PF5. However, the pairwise comparisons among PF3, PF4, and PF5 are not statistically distinguishable. Rather than supporting a continuous stepwise increase in ministerial continuity, the evidence suggests the emergence of a new historical regime characterized by substantially greater organizational continuity than that observed during the first two Political Frameworks.

The sixth Political Framework departs sharply from this pattern. Its replacement hazard is significantly higher than those observed under PF3, PF4, and PF5, reinforcing the interpretation that the current Critical Juncture represents an unsettled historical environment rather than a completed Political Framework comparable to the previous periods.

Taken together, the Kaplan--Meier estimates and the pairwise Cox comparisons provide qualified support for Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}. The evidence is inconsistent with the proposition's strongest formulation requiring a monotonic increase across every successive Political Framework. Nevertheless, it supports the broader theoretical expectation that Peru's organizational conditions for institutional continuity improved substantially relative to the earliest historical environments. The principal exception is the post-1993 Political Framework, which interrupts the earlier trajectory of increasing continuity despite representing a durable political legacy within the comparative-historical reconstruction. This finding suggests that the historical evolution of Peru's political institutions and the organizational conditions for institutional learning followed partially independent trajectories.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Proposition 2: Ministerial Duration across Governmental Organizations}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration} predicts that governmental organizations operating within the same Political Framework should exhibit systematically different patterns of ministerial duration according to the organizational protection surrounding their accumulated knowledge. Its observable implication is therefore that ministerial survival should differ across governmental organizations while holding the historical environment constant. Under Axiom~\ref{ax:protective_belt}, comparatively longer ministerial duration is interpreted as evidence consistent with stronger Protective Belts preserving organizational continuity.

The principal comparison concerns the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) and the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM). As discussed in the previous section, these organizations occupy comparable positions within the executive branch but perform fundamentally different organizational functions. The MEF concentrates specialized macroeconomic capabilities whose effectiveness depends heavily upon accumulated organizational knowledge, whereas the PCM serves primarily as the executive's principal organization for political coordination. If Protective Belts emerge selectively around organizational knowledge that is particularly valuable to the prevailing Political Framework, the MEF should exhibit greater ministerial continuity than the PCM within each historical environment.

Figure~\ref{fig:km_portfolios} therefore presents Kaplan--Meier estimates comparing ministerial survival in the MEF and the PCM separately for each Political Framework.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsubsection{Kaplan--Meier Estimates}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The Kaplan--Meier estimates provide an initial visual assessment of Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration}. Unlike Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}, the second proposition does not predict a historical ordering among Political Frameworks. Instead, it evaluates whether governmental organizations exhibit systematically different patterns of ministerial continuity while operating within the same historical environment.

The principal empirical comparison therefore concerns the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) and the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM). As discussed in the previous section, both organizations occupy central positions within the executive branch and are indispensable to the operation of government. The comparison is therefore not between organizations of unequal political importance, but between organizations performing fundamentally different organizational functions. Whereas the PCM is responsible for political coordination and coalition management, the MEF concentrates the specialized technical capabilities required for macroeconomic governance.

Under Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration}, organizational differences should emerge while holding the Political Framework constant. Figure~\ref{fig:km_pcm_mef_by_pf} therefore presents separate Kaplan--Meier estimates for each Political Framework, allowing ministerial continuity to be compared between the MEF and the PCM under the same historical conditions. If Protective Belts selectively preserve organizational continuity, the MEF should exhibit consistently higher survival probabilities than the PCM across completed Political Frameworks.

\begin{figure}[!htbp]
\centering
<<fig:km_pcm_mef_by_pf, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE, fig.width=9, fig.height=6>>=
library(survival)
library(survminer)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF")) |>
  mutate(
    portfolio = factor(
      as.character(portfolio),
      levels = c("PCM", "MEF")
    ),
    political_framework = factor(as.character(political_framework))
  )

km_pcm_mef_pf <- survfit(
  Surv(duration, event) ~ portfolio + political_framework,
  data = datos_pcm_mef
)

s_pcm_mef_pf <- surv_summary(km_pcm_mef_pf) |>
  tidyr::separate(
    strata,
    into = c("portfolio_str", "pf_str"),
    sep = ", ",
    remove = FALSE
  ) |>
  mutate(
    portfolio = gsub("^portfolio=", "", portfolio_str),
    political_framework = gsub("^political_framework=", "", pf_str)
  )

ggplot(
  s_pcm_mef_pf,
  aes(
    x = time,
    y = surv,
    colour = portfolio,
    linetype = portfolio
  )
) +geom_hline(
    yintercept = 0.5,
    linetype = "dashed",
    colour = "grey50",
    alpha = 0.6
  )+
  geom_step(linewidth = 1.1) +
  geom_hline(
    yintercept = 0.5,
    linetype = "dashed",
    colour = "grey60",
    alpha = 0.6
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ political_framework, ncol = 3) +
  labs(
    x = "Ministerial duration in days",
    y = "Survival probability",
    colour = NULL,
    linetype = NULL
  ) +
  scale_color_brewer(type = "qual", palette = "Dark2") +
  theme_classic2() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.key = element_blank(),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey70"),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold")
  )
@
\caption{Kaplan--Meier estimates of ministerial continuity for the MEF and PCM within Political Frameworks. Curves represent the estimated probability that a minister remains in office beyond a given duration. Facets hold the Political Framework constant while comparing ministerial portfolios.}
\label{fig:km_pcm_mef_by_pf}
\end{figure}


The Kaplan--Meier estimates provide an initial visual assessment of Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration}. Unlike Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_duration}, the second proposition does not predict a historical ordering among Political Frameworks. Instead, it evaluates whether organizational differences in ministerial continuity emerge while the historical environment remains constant. Each panel therefore compares the two organizations within the same Political Framework.

The comparison is theoretically demanding because both the MEF and the PCM occupy central positions within the executive branch. Neither organization can be considered politically peripheral. The PCM serves as the executive's principal organization for political coordination, whereas the MEF performs the central functions of macroeconomic governance. Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration} therefore does not compare organizations of different institutional importance, but organizations of comparable executive centrality performing fundamentally different organizational functions.

The first two Political Frameworks reveal little systematic difference between the two organizations. Beginning with the third Political Framework, however, the survival trajectories begin to separate. The divergence becomes particularly pronounced under the fourth and fifth Political Frameworks, where ministers in the MEF consistently exhibit higher survival probabilities than their counterparts in the PCM. This pattern is consistent with the expectation that the organizational capabilities embedded within macroeconomic governance became progressively more costly to disrupt as Peru's post-reform institutional settlement consolidated. By contrast, the sixth Political Framework again exhibits little separation between the two organizations, consistent with the broader organizational instability associated with the ongoing Critical Juncture.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsubsection{Cox Proportional Hazards Model with Presidential Frailty}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The Kaplan--Meier estimates compare the observed survival trajectories of the MEF and the PCM within each Political Framework, but they do not account for unobserved heterogeneity across presidential administrations. This is especially important for Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration}, since some presidents may be systematically more prone to cabinet turnover than others. To account for this executive-level dependence, the Cox models include a shared frailty term for presidential administration.

For each Political Framework, the model estimates whether MEF ministers face a different hazard of replacement than PCM ministers while allowing ministerial spells under the same president to share unobserved administration-specific risk. Hazard ratios below one indicate that MEF ministers face a lower replacement hazard than PCM ministers within the same Political Framework.

<<tab:cox_p2_frailty_interaction, results=tex, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
library(survival)
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(tibble)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF")) |>
  mutate(
    portfolio = relevel(factor(as.character(portfolio)), ref = "PCM"),
    political_framework = factor(as.character(political_framework)),
    President = factor(as.character(President))
  )

cox_p2_frailty_interaction <- coxph(
  Surv(duration, event) ~
    portfolio * political_framework +
    frailty(President),
  data = datos_pcm_mef
)

b <- coef(cox_p2_frailty_interaction)
V <- vcov(cox_p2_frailty_interaction)

coef_names <- names(b)
pf_levels <- levels(datos_pcm_mef$political_framework)

get_mef_contrast <- function(pf) {
  
  L <- setNames(rep(0, length(b)), coef_names)
  L["portfolioMEF"] <- 1
  
  if (pf != pf_levels[1]) {
    interaction_term_1 <- paste0("portfolioMEF:political_framework", pf)
    interaction_term_2 <- paste0("political_framework", pf, ":portfolioMEF")
    
    if (interaction_term_1 %in% coef_names) {
      L[interaction_term_1] <- 1
    } else if (interaction_term_2 %in% coef_names) {
      L[interaction_term_2] <- 1
    }
  }
  
  log_hr <- sum(L * b)
  se <- sqrt(as.numeric(t(L) %*% V %*% L))
  z <- log_hr / se
  
  tibble(
    `Political Framework` = pf,
    HR = exp(log_hr),
    CI_low = exp(log_hr - 1.96 * se),
    CI_high = exp(log_hr + 1.96 * se),
    p_value = 2 * pnorm(abs(z), lower.tail = FALSE)
  )
}

p2_contrasts <- map_dfr(pf_levels, get_mef_contrast) |>
  mutate(
    `Hazard ratio` = sprintf("%.2f", HR),
    `95\\% CI` = sprintf("[%.2f, %.2f]", CI_low, CI_high),
    `p-value` = format.pval(p_value, digits = 3, eps = .001)
  ) |>
  select(
    `Political Framework`,
    `Hazard ratio`,
    `95\\% CI`,
    `p-value`
  )

p2_contrasts |>
  kbl(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    align = c("l", "c", "c", "c"),
    caption = "MEF--PCM Hazard Ratios within Political Frameworks",
    label = "cox_p2_frailty_interaction",
    escape = FALSE
  ) |>
  kable_styling(
    latex_options = "hold_position",
    font_size = 9
  ) |>
  footnote(
    general = paste(
      "Hazard ratios compare MEF ministers to PCM ministers within each Political Framework.",
      "Values below one indicate a lower hazard of ministerial replacement for MEF ministers relative to PCM ministers.",
      "Estimates are derived from a single Cox proportional hazards model including portfolio, Political Framework, their interaction, and a shared frailty term for presidential administration.",
      "Reported p-values correspond to pre-specified within-framework MEF--PCM contrasts."
    ),
    threeparttable = TRUE,
    escape = FALSE
  )
@

The frailty-adjusted Cox model provides more qualified evidence than the Kaplan--Meier estimates. Across most Political Frameworks, the MEF--PCM difference is not statistically distinguishable once unobserved presidential-level heterogeneity is taken into account. The exception is PF5, where MEF ministers face a substantially lower replacement hazard than PCM ministers ($HR=0.63$, $p=0.073$). Although this contrast falls short of conventional levels of statistical significance, its magnitude and direction are consistent with the expectation that the post-1993 settlement generated stronger organizational protection around macroeconomic governance.

These results suggest that Proposition~\ref{prop:portfolio_duration} receives limited but theoretically meaningful support. Protective Belts do not appear as a general property of the MEF across the entire republican period. Rather, the evidence indicates that the MEF advantage emerges most clearly under the fifth Political Framework, precisely the period in which macroeconomic governance became central to the operation of the post-1990 political settlement.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Robustness Analysis: The Organizational Consolidation of Globalization}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\subsection{Robustness to the Organizational Consolidation of Globalization}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The previous analyses operationalized historical environments using the Political Frameworks derived from completed Critical Junctures. As discussed in Section~..., however, the organizational consolidation of Peru's post-1990 macroeconomic institutions occurred gradually throughout the subsequent decade rather than immediately following the 1993 constitutional settlement. Consequently, the fifth Political Framework potentially combines two distinct organizational environments: an initial period during which the organizational reconstruction remained incomplete and a later period in which the post-reform institutional architecture had largely consolidated.

The analyses reported below therefore examine whether the principal findings remain robust after partitioning the fifth Political Framework according to the consolidation of the globalization reforms.
<<tab:cox_p2_globalization_cut, results=tex, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
library(survival)
library(dplyr)
library(tibble)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

datos_pcm_mef_global <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF")) |>
  mutate(
    portfolio = relevel(factor(as.character(portfolio)), ref = "PCM"),
    globalization_period = case_when(
      year < 2001 ~ "1821--2000",
      year >= 2001 ~ "2001--Present"
    ),
    globalization_period = factor(
      globalization_period,
      levels = c("1821--2000", "2001--Present")
    ),
    President = factor(as.character(President))
  )

cox_p2_globalization <- coxph(
  Surv(duration, event) ~
    portfolio * globalization_period +
    frailty(President),
  data = datos_pcm_mef_global
)

b <- coef(cox_p2_globalization)
V <- vcov(cox_p2_globalization)
coef_names <- names(b)

get_mef_contrast_global <- function(period) {
  
  L <- setNames(rep(0, length(b)), coef_names)
  L["portfolioMEF"] <- 1
  
  if (period != "1821--2000") {
    interaction_term_1 <- paste0("portfolioMEF:globalization_period", period)
    interaction_term_2 <- paste0("globalization_period", period, ":portfolioMEF")
    
    if (interaction_term_1 %in% coef_names) {
      L[interaction_term_1] <- 1
    } else if (interaction_term_2 %in% coef_names) {
      L[interaction_term_2] <- 1
    }
  }
  
  log_hr <- sum(L * b)
  se <- sqrt(as.numeric(t(L) %*% V %*% L))
  z <- log_hr / se
  
  tibble(
    Period = period,
    HR = exp(log_hr),
    CI_low = exp(log_hr - 1.96 * se),
    CI_high = exp(log_hr + 1.96 * se),
    p_value = 2 * pnorm(abs(z), lower.tail = FALSE)
  )
}

p2_globalization_contrasts <- lapply(
  levels(datos_pcm_mef_global$globalization_period),
  get_mef_contrast_global
) |>
  bind_rows() |>
  mutate(
    `Hazard ratio` = sprintf("%.2f", HR),
    `95\\% CI` = sprintf("[%.2f, %.2f]", CI_low, CI_high),
    `p-value` = format.pval(p_value, digits = 3, eps = .001)
  ) |>
  select(
    Period,
    `Hazard ratio`,
    `95\\% CI`,
    `p-value`
  )

p2_globalization_contrasts |>
  kbl(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    align = c("l", "c", "c", "c"),
    caption = "MEF--PCM Hazard Ratios before and after Globalization Consolidation",
    label = "cox_p2_globalization_cut",
    escape = FALSE
  ) |>
  kable_styling(
    latex_options = "hold_position",
    font_size = 9
  ) |>
  footnote(
    general = paste(
      "Hazard ratios compare MEF ministers to PCM ministers within each period.",
      "Values below one indicate a lower hazard of ministerial replacement for MEF ministers relative to PCM ministers.",
      "The cut at 2001 distinguishes the historical period before and after the consolidation of the post-1990 globalization reforms.",
      "Estimates are derived from a single Cox proportional hazards model including portfolio, period, their interaction, and a shared frailty term for presidential administration.",
      "Reported p-values correspond to pre-specified MEF--PCM contrasts within each period."
    ),
    threeparttable = TRUE,
    escape = FALSE
  )
@




The globalization cut clarifies the historical pattern suggested by the Political Framework analysis. Before 2001, MEF and PCM ministers exhibit virtually identical replacement hazards ($HR=1.04$). After 2001, the MEF hazard falls below the PCM hazard ($HR=0.70$), indicating a roughly 30 percent lower risk of ministerial replacement. Although this contrast is not statistically significant at conventional levels, its direction and magnitude are consistent with the interpretation that the organizational advantage of the MEF emerges only after the consolidation of the post-1990 globalization reforms.

<<tab:cox_all_portfolios_global, results=tex, echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
library(survival)
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(tibble)
library(knitr)
library(kableExtra)

datos_all <- gatopardo |>
  filter(portfolio %in% c("MEF", "PCM", "Interior", "Educacion", "Salud")) |>
  mutate(
    portfolio = factor(
      as.character(portfolio),
      levels = c("MEF", "PCM", "Interior", "Educacion", "Salud")
    ),
    globalization_period = factor(
      ifelse(year < 2001, "1821--2000", "2001--Present"),
      levels = c("1821--2000", "2001--Present")
    ),
    President = factor(as.character(President))
  )

fit_all <- coxph(
  Surv(duration, event) ~
    portfolio * globalization_period +
    frailty(President),
  data = datos_all
)

b <- coef(fit_all)
V <- vcov(fit_all)
coef_names <- names(b)

get_portfolio_contrast <- function(port, period) {
  
  L <- setNames(rep(0, length(b)), coef_names)
  
  # Portfolio contrast against MEF in baseline period
  port_term <- paste0("portfolio", port)
  if (port_term %in% coef_names) {
    L[port_term] <- 1
  }
  
  # Add interaction for post-2001 period
  if (period == "2001--Present") {
    int1 <- paste0("portfolio", port, ":globalization_period", period)
    int2 <- paste0("globalization_period", period, ":portfolio", port)
    
    if (int1 %in% coef_names) {
      L[int1] <- 1
    } else if (int2 %in% coef_names) {
      L[int2] <- 1
    }
  }
  
  log_hr <- sum(L * b)
  se <- sqrt(as.numeric(t(L) %*% V %*% L))
  z <- log_hr / se
  
  tibble(
    Portfolio = recode(
      port,
      "Educacion" = "Education",
      "Salud" = "Health"
    ),
    Period = period,
    HR = exp(log_hr),
    CI_low = exp(log_hr - 1.96 * se),
    CI_high = exp(log_hr + 1.96 * se),
    p_value = 2 * pnorm(abs(z), lower.tail = FALSE)
  )
}

tab_all <- expand.grid(
  Portfolio = c("PCM", "Interior", "Educacion", "Salud"),
  Period = c("1821--2000", "2001--Present"),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
) |>
  pmap_dfr(~ get_portfolio_contrast(..1, ..2)) |>
  mutate(
    `Hazard ratio` = sprintf("%.2f", HR),
    `95\\% CI` = sprintf("[%.2f, %.2f]", CI_low, CI_high),
    `p-value` = format.pval(p_value, digits = 3, eps = .001)
  ) |>
  select(
    Period,
    Portfolio,
    `Hazard ratio`,
    `95\\% CI`,
    `p-value`
  )

tab_all |>
  kbl(
    format = "latex",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    align = c("l", "l", "c", "c", "c"),
    caption = "Ministerial Replacement Relative to the MEF before and after Globalization Consolidation",
    label = "cox_all_portfolios_global",
    escape = FALSE
  ) |>
  kable_styling(
    latex_options = c("hold_position"),
    font_size = 9
  ) |>
  footnote(
    general = paste(
      "Hazard ratios compare each portfolio to the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) within each period.",
      "Values above one indicate a greater hazard of ministerial replacement than the MEF.",
      "Estimates are derived from a single Cox proportional hazards model including portfolio, globalization period, their interaction, and a shared frailty term for presidential administration.",
      "Reported p-values correspond to pre-specified within-period portfolio contrasts relative to the MEF."
    ),
    threeparttable = TRUE,
    escape = FALSE
  )
@

Table~\ref{tab:cox_all_portfolios_global} extends the MEF comparison to the broader set of governmental organizations. Before 2001, the MEF does not exhibit a general continuity advantage. The PCM and Interior portfolios are statistically indistinguishable from the MEF, while Education and Health exhibit significantly lower replacement hazards. After 2001, however, the pattern changes. The PCM and Interior portfolios display higher replacement hazards than the MEF, with the Interior contrast reaching conventional levels of statistical significance. Education and Health remain statistically indistinguishable from the MEF.

These results reinforce the interpretation that the MEF advantage is historically contingent rather than inherent to the portfolio. The evidence does not suggest that the MEF was consistently protected throughout the republican period. Instead, its relative continuity becomes more apparent after the consolidation of the post-1990 globalization reforms, particularly when compared to organizations more directly exposed to political coordination, internal security, and recurrent crisis management.

